> As far as I'm aware, most third-party package managers work the same way as `vim.pack`, where they do not load plugins that are not explicitly declared in code. For instance, `lazy.nvim` and `mini.deps` both behave this way.

You're right that many plugin managers work the way you describe, but there are plugin managers that work in other ways. They will install to start/ (if the user wants), and they don't have to run every time that Neovim starts. Neovim, like Vim, already has mechanisms to load plugins. You don't necessarily need a plugin manager to control that.

@weilbith, take a look at [paq.nvim](https://github.com/savq/paq-nvim). In particular, look for the Bootstraping section in the docs. ([This is what I used](https://github.com/telemachus/dotfiles/blob/2f66f2eef9df92aeeaad2df1e04ad7e4c9fe3108/config/nvim/lua/headless.lua) for a long time. You can have a cron job start Neovim in headless mode and run a script like that however often you want. When Neovim starts, no plugin manager runs, just the editor.)
